        "client_msg_id": "4a6576b4-7a9f-4e57-9479-c661b4419b3c",
        "text": "2. Yes, the reporter's analysis is correct. The only case in which the current example would spit out `NA` is when both `x` and `y` are 0.\nThis is not only true if the length of `x` and `y` is 31, but for any odd length greater than 1. The reason is that for any odd length greater than 1, there would be one instance of 0 in both x and y. For that value of x and y, the defined function `f`  inside the example code returns `NaN` . However, for even lengths, there would be no 0 values in `x` and `y` .",
